YOUR LAB CHEAT SHEET
  
  A. Start the server (over SSH from the laptop, or in person)

  ssh janga@<DESKTOP_TAILSCALE_IP>      # or:  ssh janga@<DESKTOP_TAILNET_HOSTNAME>
  ~/start_navila_server.sh

  Wait for [server] listening on 0.0.0.0:5555 — Ctrl-C to exit. (~5 s).
  Leave the SSH session open or run via tmux/screen/nohup.

  B. First robot contact — climb the ladder

  1. Joystick first (10 minutes).  Power on the K1, pair the joystick,
  walk it around manually. Confirm:
  - emergency stop on the joystick works
  - robot enters/exits walking mode cleanly
  - battery is healthy
  
  2. SDK sanity (5 minutes).  Cable in the laptop, then on the laptop:
  conda activate navila        # or activate whatever env has the SDK
  python ~/Projects/k1_research/booster/booster_robotics_sdk/example/high_
  level/b1_loco_example_client.py 192.168.10.102
  # type 'gm' (get mode), 'mp' (kPrepare), 'mw' (kWalking), small 'w'/'s' 
  commands, then 'md' (kDamping)
  This confirms the Ethernet + SDK link is healthy without NaVILA in the
  loop.
  
  3. Print mode (no robot motion at all).  End-to-end NaVILA pipeline
  smoke test using a static image:
  python ~/Projects/k1_research/experiments/navila/navila_laptop_relay.py
  \
      --mode print \
      --image-source static \
      --image-path ~/Projects/k1_research/experiments/vla/test_image.jpg \
      --server <DESKTOP_TAILSCALE_IP> \
      --instruction "walk forward 1 meter"
  You should see HUD + would send Move(...) lines and a clean exit.

  4. Dry mode on the powered K1 (no motion, but full SDK).
  python ~/Projects/k1_research/experiments/navila/navila_laptop_relay.py
  \
      --mode dry \
      --image-source mjpeg --mjpeg-url http://192.168.10.102:8080/stream \
      --server <DESKTOP_TAILSCALE_IP> \
      --net 192.168.10.102 \ 
      --instruction "walk forward 1 meter"
  (Use --image-source dir --image-dir <recorded> if the K1 doesn't have an
   MJPEG stream up.) [actuator/dry] would send Move(...) lines should
  appear; the K1 will NOT move.
  
  5. Live, floor cleared, kill switch in hand.
  python ~/Projects/k1_research/experiments/navila/navila_laptop_relay.py
  \
      --mode live \
      --image-source mjpeg --mjpeg-url http://192.168.10.102:8080/stream \
      --server <DESKTOP_TAILSCALE_IP> \
      --net 192.168.10.102 \ 
      --instruction "walk forward 1 meter"
  Test the kill path first: start it, then immediately press q in the HUD
  window. Confirm the robot stops within ~1.5 s. Only after that, run an
  actual instruction.

  C. Emergency-stop options (in order of preference)

  1. Joystick e-stop — physical, always works
  2. q in the HUD window — zeros Move, switches K1 to kDamping, exits
  cleanly
  3. Ctrl-C in the relay terminal — same SIGINT handler
  4. Pull the Ethernet cable — laptop's 1.5 s watchdog zeroes Move, then
  the K1's own loss-of-link logic kicks in
  5. Kill the relay process — same as 4
  6. Power switch — last resort

  D. If something goes wrong

  symptom: [remote] connecting to <DESKTOP_TAILSCALE_IP>:5555 ... hangs
  most likely cause: server not running, or ufw blocks Tailscale
  fix: on desktop: check ~/start_navila_server.sh shell. If needed: sudo 
    ufw allow in on tailscale0 to any port 5555
  ────────────────────────────────────────
  symptom: connection refused
  most likely cause: server crashed / not started
  fix: re-run ~/start_navila_server.sh
  ────────────────────────────────────────
  symptom: [remote] network error: timed out
  most likely cause: NaVILA wedged or Tailscale slow
  fix: restart server, check tailscale status
  ────────────────────────────────────────
  symptom: import booster_robotics_sdk_python fails on laptop
  most likely cause: SDK wheel not installed
  fix: ./setup_laptop.sh re-run, or build from source per REMOTE_README.md
  ────────────────────────────────────────
  symptom: HUD buf=0 forever
  most likely cause: server isn't decoding frames
  fix: check --jpeg-quality; default 80 is fine
  ────────────────────────────────────────
  symptom: robot drifts on "walk forward"
  most likely cause: known NaVILA bias, no heading-assist without pose
  fix: acceptable for short distances; live with it for v1
  ────────────────────────────────────────
  symptom: robot spins forever on "turn N deg"
  most likely cause: --turn-controller on without pose
  fix: use --no-turn-controller (already the laptop default — only happens

    if you flipped it)
  ────────────────────────────────────────
  symptom: Move() calls don't seem to move the robot
  most likely cause: wrong --net, robot not in kWalking
  fix: double-check --net 192.168.10.102; verify with
    b1_loco_example_client.py first

